{"id":"1911.02860","submitter":"Masahito Hayashi","authors":"Masahito Hayashi and Seunghoan Song","title":"Quantum Capacity of Partially Corrupted Quantum Network","comments":null,"journal-ref":"Phys. Rev. Research 2, 033079 (2020)","doi":"10.1103/PhysRevResearch.2.033079","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We discuss a quantum network, in which the sender has $m_0$ outgoing\nchannels, the receiver has $m_0$ incoming channels, each channel is of capacity\n$d$, each intermediate node applies invertible unitary, only $m_1$ channels are\ncorrupted, and other non-corrupted channels are noiseless. As our result, we\nshow that the quantum capacity is not smaller than $(m_0-2m_1+1)\\log d$ under\nthe following two settings. In the first case, the unitaries on intermediate\nnodes are arbitrary and the corruptions on the $m_1$ channels are individual.\nIn the second case, the unitaries on intermediate nodes are restricted to\nClifford operations and the corruptions on the $m_1$ channels are adaptive,\ni.e., the attacker is allowed to have a quantum memory. Further, our code in\nthe second case realizes the noiseless communication even with the single-shot\nsetting and is constructed dependently only on the network topology and the\nplaces of the $m_1$ corrupted channels while this result holds regardless of\nthe network topology and the places.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 7 Nov 2019 11:32:40 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-07-22"}
